{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9cf2f791-4a4a-4df8-b096-7010d25eb70e","content":"The template is **functional but not fully ready** for NuGet publishing. Here's what I found:\n\n**✅ Present & correct:** `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, `tags` (language + type), `symbols`\n\n**⚠️ Missing or recommended fields:**\n\n| Field | Status | Why it matters |\n|---|---|---|\n| `$schema` | Missing | Enables validation & IntelliSense |\n| `description` | Missing | Required for discoverability on NuGet |\n| `groupIdentity` | Missing | Needed to group template variants in a pack |\n| `precedence` | Missing | Controls version ordering within a group |\n| `preferNameDirectory` | Missing | Should be `true` for project templates |\n\n**📝 Other notes:**\n- The `defaultValue` for Framework is `net9.0` — consider whether `net10.0` should be offered given .NET 10 is current.\n- Ensure you have a `.nupkg` project (`.csproj` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>`) wrapping this template for NuGet publishing.\n\n**Verdict:** Add at least `description` and `groupIdentity` before publishing. The template will *install* without them, but will have poor discoverability and won't handle future variants cleanly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3c860584-58da-4114-bfff-16d5b8a9df33","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. Let me check for required and recommended fields.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not required, but recommended for validation/intellisense.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for template packs published to NuGet.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Often used alongside groupIdentity.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. **`identity`** — present ✓\n6. **`name`** — present ✓\n\n\n7. **`shortName`** — present ✓\n8. **`sourceName`** — present ✓\n9. **`author`** — present ✓\n10. **`classifications`** — present ✓\n11. **`tags`** — present, has language and type ✓\n12. **`symbols`** — present ✓\n\nThe template has most of the essential fields, but for NuGet publishing I'd want to add `$schema` for validation and `groupIdentity` so related template variants can be grouped together. I'm also noticing the Framework symbol defaults to `net9.0`, which might need consideration depending on the target audience.\n\nThere are a few other gaps worth addressing: no top-level `description` field for better discoverability, and `preferNameDirectory` isn't set to `true` as is typical for project templates. Let me look at what other files are included in this template pack.","outputTokens":700,"requestId":"A80C:1BE3:CFB297:EB1950:6A027AF5"},"id":"52ac3320-a45d-49bc-bfbc-f0cd8d7ddb8d","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:57:40.877Z","parentId":"630bf0da-ad19-4d1d-9637-fdac6230a688"}
